BTP Voice Assistant - Knowledge Transfer (KT) Document
=========================================================

Objective
---------
Create a single consolidated reference so a new reviewer can understand how the BTP Voice Assistant works end-to-end, why key design decisions were made, what data formats/contract are used, and how to troubleshoot common failures.

Investigation Log
------------------
1. Collected core documentation from repository `*.md` sources (README, architecture, design decisions, algorithms, API reference, schemas, module/data-pipeline READMEs, implementation notes).
2. Mapped the documentation into a single KT flow: user interaction loop -> component responsibilities -> data/JSON/CSV contracts -> fallbacks and limitations.
3. Consolidated “how it works” (architecture + data flow) with “why it was chosen” (design decisions) and “how to use/extend” (API reference + schemas).

Architectural Design & Rationale
---------------------------------
## System Overview (What the assistant does)
The assistant is a conversational cooking system that:
1. Listens for a wake word (“Hey Cook”) continuously.
2. Records a single user utterance after wake word detection using VAD (silence-based endpointing).
3. Transcribes speech to text (ASR).
4. Classifies the user utterance into an intent (navigation, recipe search, Q&A, small talk, control commands, etc.).
5. Retrieves and navigates recipes (steps + ingredients) or generates conversational answers.
6. Converts the response to speech (TTS) and plays audio.
7. Persists session state so the user can continue/recover across turns.

## High-level Interaction Loop (Main idea)
The runtime is designed as:
- A background daemon thread for wake word detection (always listening).
- A main thread that waits for wake word, then records, transcribes, classifies, dispatches, and speaks.

When wake word is detected while audio is playing, the player can be paused so the assistant can respond to the new command quickly. (See: `ARCHITECTURE.md`, `DESIGN_DECISIONS.md`)

## Layered view (for understanding responsibilities)
This project can be understood as four logical layers:
1. Driver Layer: Audio input/output and external API clients (Porcupine detection, ASR APIs, TTS APIs, backend recipe API, Milvus client, Redis client).
2. Session Layer: Persisting progress and conversation history (Upstash Redis with in-memory fallback).
3. Interaction Layer: Translating structured decisions into spoken/audio output (TTS chunking, audio playback pause/resume).
4. Logic Layer: Orchestrating the pipeline per turn (intent classification -> dispatch -> response generation -> session updates).

## Key Design Decisions (Why the system is built this way)
The documentation below reflects the rationale provided in `DESIGN_DECISIONS.md`:

1. Wake word detection: Picovoice Porcupine (local, always-on)
- Decision: Pre-trained Porcupine model for “Hey Cook”.
- Why: Low latency, always-on operation without blocking, privacy (audio stays local until ASR).
- Trade-offs: Vendor dependency and fixed wake word model.

2. ASR: Hybrid Deepgram (primary) + Whisper (fallback)
- Decision: Deepgram for speed/accuracy; Whisper local for resilience when cloud fails.
- Why: Deepgram keeps conversational flow responsive; Whisper preserves functionality if Deepgram is unavailable/rate-limited.
- Trade-offs: Cloud cost/internet dependency vs slower local inference.

3. Intent classification: Rule-based (primary) + Gemini LLM fallback
- Decision: Regex/rule patterns for common intents; LLM used only when confidence is low.
- Why: Fast deterministic mapping for most commands; LLM handles edge cases/paraphrases.
- Trade-offs: Rules need maintenance; LLM adds latency and can be non-deterministic (mitigated by validation/fallbacks).

4. Recipe retrieval: Milvus + SentenceTransformer embeddings
- Decision: Semantic search using 384-D embeddings (SentenceTransformer `all-MiniLM-L6-v2`) stored/indexed via Milvus.
- Why: Captures meaning beyond exact keywords (pasta ~ spaghetti ~ noodles).
- Trade-offs: Setup complexity and dataset scale considerations.

5. LLM choice: Google Gemini 2.5 Flash
- Decision: Gemini for structured response generation and fallback intent classification.
- Why: Fast enough for fallback; supports structured outputs (validated and extracted).
- Trade-offs: API dependency and potential hallucination risk (mitigated by using structured templates + API-provided recipe data).

6. Session storage: Upstash Redis (primary) + in-memory fallback
- Decision: Persist session state with TTL in Redis; fallback to in-memory dict if Redis is unavailable.
- Why: Resume after interruption/pause; easy KV model for session state.
- Trade-offs: Redis adds network/API latency; persistence depends on network availability.

7. TTS: Deepgram TTS
- Decision: Deepgram for speech synthesis.
- Why: Natural voice quality; fast enough; consistent vendor integration.
- Trade-offs: Cloud dependency and usage cost; fallback quality depends on local capabilities (not guaranteed in docs).

8. Audio playback: concurrent playback with pause/resume
- Decision: Use a chunked player with background audio handling so wake word detection remains responsive.
- Why: Users may interrupt (“next step”) while the assistant is speaking.
- Trade-offs: Thread/synchronization complexity.

9. Data format: CSV for recipe navigation data
- Decision: Use CSV files for recipe chunks and ingredient lookup.
- Why: Simplicity, version-control friendly, sufficient for read-heavy static datasets.
- Trade-offs: Not ideal for large-scale updates; relies on offline regeneration and consistent chunking.

Implementation & Rationale
---------------------------
## End-to-end Pipeline (per user turn)
The typical sequence (from `ARCHITECTURE.md` and `API_REFERENCE.md`):
1. Wake word detection
   - Triggered in background by `WakeWordDetector`.
2. Recording (VAD endpointing)
   - `ShortRecorder.record_once()` captures audio using RMS threshold + silence duration.
3. ASR transcription
   - Primary: Deepgram transcription to text.
   - Fallback: Whisper transcription locally if Deepgram is unavailable.
4. Intent classification
   - Rule-based patterns attempt classification first.
   - If rule confidence < threshold, optionally call Gemini LLM fallback.
   - Returns: `(Intent, confidence, entities)`.
5. Dispatch to intent handler
   - `SEARCH_RECIPE` -> `RecipeRetriever`
   - `NAV_*` -> `RecipeNavigator`
   - `QUESTION` / `SMALL_TALK` / other -> `RecipeLLM`
6. Response generation
   - For recipes: structured JSON response (greeting, ingredients with `spoken`, steps with `spoken`, closing).
   - For non-recipe intents: short conversational plain text response suitable for TTS.
7. Session persistence
   - Store/update current navigation position and response structure.
   - Add conversation history entries.
8. TTS synthesis
   - Split text into sentence-sized chunks and synthesize speech.
9. Audio playback
   - Play audio chunks concurrently with continued wake word listening.

## Component Responsibilities
### 1. Wake Word Detection (`modules/wakeword.py`)
- What it does: always-on detection of “Hey Cook”.
- How it works (as documented): Porcupine processes PCM frames in a daemon thread and signals detection via an internal event/flag.
- Key tuning:
  - Sensitivity (0-1 scale) affects false positives vs missed detections.
  - Pre-roll audio helps ensure the beginning of speech is captured after wake word.

### 2. Voice Activity Detection + Recording (`modules/vad.py`)
- What it does: captures a single utterance using RMS-based silence endpointing.
- How it works (as documented in `ALGORITHMS.md`):
  - Fill a pre-roll buffer (captures audio prior to speaking).
  - Record frames while energy stays above threshold.
  - Stop after `silence_duration` worth of consecutive frames have RMS energy below `silence_thresh`.
- Output contract:
  - Saves a mono PCM WAV file at 16 kHz (per schema/spec).

### 3. ASR (Deepgram primary, Whisper fallback)
- What it does: transcribes WAV to a lowercased plain text string.
- Why hybrid:
  - Deepgram optimizes latency and accuracy.
  - Whisper fallback maintains resilience when cloud calls fail.
- Output contract:
  - Stored transcription files go into `ASR_text/` as plain text lines (one-line lowercased transcript).

### 4. Intent Classification (`modules/intent_classifier.py`)
- What it does: maps transcription text to one of the supported `Intent` values.
- How it works:
  1. Rule-based regex patterns:
     - Fast evaluation, explains why an intent matched.
     - Produces `(intent, confidence, entities)`.
  2. Confidence threshold:
     - If below configured `confidence_threshold`, call Gemini LLM fallback (optional).
  3. Context boost:
     - If user continues the same intent, confidence can be slightly boosted (to reduce repeated disambiguation).
- Output contract:
  - Tuple: `(Intent enum, float confidence, Dict entities)`

### 5. Recipe Retrieval (`modules/retriever.py`)
- What it does: finds relevant recipes using semantic search.
- How it works:
  - Query embedding generated via SentenceTransformer (`all-MiniLM-L6-v2`) -> 384-D vector.
  - Milvus vector search returns top-K recipe candidates (cosine similarity).
  - Fetch full recipe details from backend API using the selected recipe_id.
- Output contract:
  - A list of dicts including `recipe_id`, `title`, `similarity_score`, and `metadata`.

### 6. Recipe Navigation (`modules/navigator.py`)
- What it does: converts a recipe and current session state into the next spoken instruction or ingredient list.
- Data sources:
  - `data/chunks.csv` drives navigation across chunks.
  - `data/food_dictionary.csv` supports ingredient listing.
- Navigation state:
  - `step_index`: global step number (0 means ingredients).
  - `chunk_index`: chunk number (1-based).
- Return contract:
  - `NavigationResult` with `success`, `intent`, `step_index`, `chunk_index`, `text`, `section`, flags like `is_last_step`.

### 7. Response Generation & Structured JSON (`modules/llm.py`)
- What it does: generate either:
  - Recipe responses as structured JSON (for step-by-step tracking and TTS chunking), or
  - Non-recipe conversational strings for small talk / Q&A.

#### Recipe Response JSON contract
When `return_json=True`, a structured response is expected to have:
- `greeting`: string
- `ingredients`: list of objects `{ "text": string, "spoken": bool }`
- `steps`: list of objects `{ "step_num": int, "text": string, "spoken": bool }`
- `closing`: string

Validation & fallback behavior (from `IMPLEMENTATION_NOTES.md` + API docs):
- Primary attempt: ask LLM for valid JSON.
- If invalid JSON:
  - Extract JSON from markdown code blocks if LLM wrapped output in ```json ... ```.
- If still invalid:
  - Manually construct a structured response from available recipe data (tertiary fallback).

#### Why structured JSON?
- It enables consistent “what to speak next” logic (and progress tracking) rather than relying on free-form text parsing.

### 8. Session State (`modules/session_manager.py`)
- What it does: persist session state to allow resume and multi-turn behavior.
- Primary backend: Upstash Redis with TTL (documented default: 3600 seconds).
- Fallback: in-memory dict if Redis is unavailable.
- Stored fields (from schemas):
  - Recipe identity: `recipe_id`, `recipe_title`
  - Navigation position: `current_step`, `current_chunk`
  - `response_structure` (LLM structured JSON)
  - `ingredients_spoken`, `steps_spoken` trackers
  - `conversation_history` and optional user preference metadata.

### 9. Text-to-Speech (`modules/tts.py`)
- What it does: convert response text into audio using Deepgram TTS.
- How it works:
  - Splits long text into chunks (sentence-friendly) before calling the API.
  - Generates MP3 output (or returns an audio path / bytes per implementation).

### 10. Audio Playback (`modules/audio_player.py`)
- What it does: plays synthesized audio while wake word detection continues running in background.
- Why chunked/concurrent:
  - Allows pause/resume and interruption so new commands can interrupt current speech.

### 11. API Reference Quick Map (key interfaces)
The following method/class names are the primary “entry points” for integration and debugging (from `API_REFERENCE.md`):

1. `WakeWordDetector` (wake word)
   - `start()`, `is_detected()`, `wait_for_detected(timeout)`, `stop()`
2. `ShortRecorder` (VAD + recording)
   - `rms(pcm)`, `record_once(out_path="temp.wav")`
3. `IntentClassifier`
   - `classify(text, context=None) -> (Intent, confidence, entities)`
4. `RecipeRetriever` (semantic retrieval)
   - `embed_query(query_text)`, `search_recipes(query_text, top_k=5)`, `fetch_full_recipe_details(recipe_id)`
5. `RecipeNavigator` (step navigation)
   - `load_recipe(recipe_id)`, `get_current_step(session)`, `get_next_step(session)`, `get_previous_step(session)`,
     `jump_to_step(session, target_step)`, `get_current_ingredients(session)`, `restart(session)`
6. `RecipeLLM` (response generation)
   - `generate_recipe_response(user_query, recipe_results, return_json=True, conversation_history=None)`
   - `generate_conversational_response(user_query, current_recipe=None, session_context=None, conversation_history=None)`
   - `answer_recipe_question(question, recipe_context, conversation_history=None)`
7. `SessionManager`
   - `create_session(...)`, `get_session(session_id)`, `update_session(session_id, updates)`,
     `add_to_history(session_id, role, content)`, `get_history(session_id, limit=10)`
8. `RecipeTTS`
   - `generate_speech(text, output_file=None)`, `split_into_chunks(text, max_chunk_length=300)`
9. `ChunkedAudioPlayer`
   - `play_chunks(mp3_chunks)`, `pause()`, `resume()`, `stop()`

## Data Contracts & Schemas (What must match)
This project relies on explicit contracts. The following are the most important ones from `SCHEMAS.md`:

### ASR output
- Deepgram listens return JSON, but the stored representation in `ASR_text/` is:
  - plain text, one line, lowercased.

### Intent classification output
- `(Intent, confidence, entities)` tuple.
- Entities are intent-dependent (e.g., `target_step` for navigation, `ingredient` for substitution questions).

### LLM structured recipe response (RecipeLLM)
- Must include keys: `greeting`, `ingredients`, `steps`, `closing`.
- Validation rules:
  - ingredients list items must contain `text`
  - steps list items must contain `step_num` and `text`
  - “spoken” is initially false.

### NavigationResult (navigator)
- Contains: `success`, `intent`, `step_index`, `chunk_index`, `text`, `section`, `is_last_step`, etc.

### CSV formats for navigation
- `data/chunks.csv`:
  - includes chunk step ranges (`start_step`, `end_step`) and chunk text for navigation.
- `data/recipes.csv`, `data/food_dictionary.csv`:
  - support recipe metadata and ingredient lookup.

### Environment variables
Key required configuration is documented in `SCHEMAS.md` and used by components:
- `DEEPGRAM_API_KEY`
- `Gemini_API_key`
- `API_BASE_URL`
- `REDIS_URL` (optional, used if configured)

Capabilities & Limitations
--------------------------
## Capabilities
1. Always-on “Hey Cook” wake word detection (local on device).
2. Single-utterance recording using RMS-based VAD endpointing.
3. Speech-to-text with a resilient ASR pipeline (Deepgram primary, Whisper fallback).
4. Hybrid intent classification (rules first, LLM fallback when uncertain).
5. Semantic recipe retrieval using Milvus embeddings.
6. Step-by-step navigation over pre-chunked recipe CSV data.
7. Recipe responses as structured JSON, enabling progress tracking and deterministic navigation.
8. Session persistence with resume behavior (Redis TTL; fallback in-memory).
9. Speech output with chunked TTS and concurrent playback for interruption.

## Limitations
1. VAD tuning is environment-dependent
- Kitchen noise can affect RMS thresholding; the system needs threshold/duration tuning for different environments.
2. Rule-based intent classification requires maintenance
- Rules can miss paraphrases and may need updates as interaction style changes.
3. LLM latency and non-determinism
- LLM fallback adds delay (by design) and can fail to output valid structured JSON, which is mitigated via extraction + validation + fallback creation.
4. Cloud dependencies and costs
- Deepgram ASR/TTS and Gemini calls depend on network connectivity and usage-based costs.
5. Structured response assumes consistent schema compliance
- If schema validation fails, fallback strategy determines output quality.
6. CSV data model is best for static/mostly read-only datasets
- For frequent updates or very large dynamic datasets, the CSV + regeneration approach may become limiting.

Advanced Techniques
--------------------
## Cascading fallbacks (graceful degradation)
The system is designed to keep functioning even if a component fails:
1. ASR: Deepgram -> Whisper fallback
2. Intent classification: rule confidence -> Gemini fallback -> UNKNOWN (if LLM unavailable)
3. LLM recipe JSON: JSON mode -> extract JSON from markdown -> manual structured construction
4. Session storage: Redis -> in-memory fallback
These strategies are documented in `DESIGN_DECISIONS.md`, `API_REFERENCE.md`, and `SCHEMAS.md`.

## Confidence thresholding + context boost
- Rule-based intent classification uses a confidence threshold so only uncertain cases trigger LLM fallback.
- Additional confidence boost can be applied when the user continues the same intent across turns.

## Embedding-based retrieval with cosine similarity
- SentenceTransformer embeddings + Milvus nearest neighbor search uses cosine similarity to find semantically similar recipes.

## Chunk boundary logic (recipe navigation)
- Recipes are divided into chunks based on steps to make navigation coherent.
- Chunk boundaries aim to respect natural breaks rather than splitting mid-instruction.

## TTS-friendly chunking
- Long text responses are split into chunks based on sentence boundaries to optimize TTS latency and intelligibility.

Troubleshooting & Incident Log
-------------------------------
## Troubleshooting (pre-documented mitigations)
1. “No audio response” or repeated failures
- Check whether Deepgram API credentials (`DEEPGRAM_API_KEY`) are configured and network access is available.
2. “Can’t classify intent correctly”
- Ensure `confidence_threshold` is appropriate; if too high, LLM fallback might be overused, causing latency.
3. “LLM recipe output is missing fields”
- The system attempts JSON extraction and schema validation; if validation fails, it uses a manual structured response fallback.
4. “Session doesn’t resume”
- If Redis is unreachable/unconfigured, session will fall back to in-memory and will not persist across restarts.
5. “VAD cuts off speech too early”
- Increase `silence_duration` or adjust `silence_thresh` to tolerate kitchen noise.

## Incident Log
No runtime incidents (with exact error messages and resolution steps) are recorded in the current documentation set.
If an error occurs during execution, append it here following the incident template used in this project’s documentation style.

